@NODE Problems
»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»
» 12) Problems:                                                            »
»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»»

- LeftyMouse could cause a few problems:

Programs  which  do  special things with the mousebuttons like DirectoryOpus
and DPaint react strange.  But as I noticed, this seems to be a problem with
any "leftymouse"-program.

However, I'm righthanded. ;-)

If  anybody discovers (or doesn't) this problems with other programs using a
leftymouse-feature, I will be happy to hear (or read) about it.


- If you have problems controling other programs like KCommodity, this could
be  because KCommodity uses an inputhandler with a priority higher (standard
55) then the commodity-network (53) itself.

Set  the  inputhandler-priority for the naughty program lower then 53 and it
should work.

-  Some  programs  don't  allow  a  change  of  their inputhandler-priority.
Because of that they can't receive events from a commodity (like this).  The
only  thing  I  could  do  about  it, is to change the event-handling from a
commodity-routine  to  a  inputhandler-routine.   But, for now, I don't have
motivation for that.  Sorry.  ;-)

